Confidentiality: high — salary is sensitive personal/financial data; restrict via least-privilege RBAC, column-level access controls, encryption at rest and in transit, masking/tokenization for non-privileged roles, and audit logging of reads. Integrity: high — must be accurate and tamper-evident; enforce with constraints, change auditing, segregation of duties, and signed/immutable payroll records. Availability: medium — needed for payroll/HR operations on schedule; ensure backups, replication, and documented RTO/RPO. Under GDPR salary is personal data (Art. 4(1)) but not a special category under Art. 9; lawful bases are typically Art. 6(1)(b) contract and (1)(c) legal obligation (tax, social security), with (1)(f) legitimate interest only for narrow ancillary uses. Apply data-minimization, purpose limitation, and storage limitation aligned to statutory retention (e.g., tax/payroll periods); honor data-subject rights (access, rectification, restriction) and log processing activities (Art. 30). Cross-border transfers require Art. 46 safeguards (SCCs + TIA). Conduct a DPIA if used for profiling, performance scoring, or automated decision-making (Art. 22/35). Document the column in the RoPA with classification "Confidential – Personal Data (Financial)".
